# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: deb-packaging
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:deb-packaging/apt-software] APT is a collection of tools distributed in a package named *apt*.
[src:deb-packaging/apt-software] A significant part of APT is defined in a C++ library of functions; APT also includes command-line programs for dealing with packages, which use the library.
[src:deb-packaging/apt-software] Three such programs are `apt`, `apt-get` and `apt-cache`.
[src:deb-packaging/apt-software] They are commonly used in examples because they are simple and ubiquitous.
[src:deb-packaging/apt-software] The *apt* package is of "*important*" priority in all current Debian releases, and is therefore included in a default Debian installation.
[src:deb-packaging/apt-software] APT can be considered a front end to `dpkg`, friendlier than the older `dselect` front end.
[src:deb-packaging/apt-software] While `dpkg` performs actions on individual packages, APT manages relations (especially dependencies) between them, as well as sourcing and management of higher-level versioning decisions such as release tracking and Upgrade Suppression.
[src:deb-packaging/apt-software] APT is often hailed as one of Debian's best features, which Debian developers attribute to the strict quality controls in Debian's policy.
[src:deb-packaging/apt-software] A major feature of APT is the way it calls `dpkg` –it performs topological sorting of the list of packages to be installed or removed and calls `dpkg` in the best possible sequence.
[src:deb-packaging/apt-software] In some cases, it utilizes the `--force` options of `dpkg`.
[src:deb-packaging/apt-software] However, it only does this when it is unable to calculate how to avoid the reason `dpkg` requires the action to be forced.
[src:deb-packaging/apt-software] The user indicates one or more packages to be installed.
[src:deb-packaging/apt-software] Each package name is phrased as just the name portion of the package, not a fully qualified filename (for instance, in a Debian system, `libc6` would be the argument provided, not `libc6_1.9.6-2.deb`).
[src:deb-packaging/apt-software] Notably, APT automatically gets and installs packages upon which the indicated package depends (if necessary).
[src:deb-packaging/apt-software] This was an original distinguishing characteristic of APT-based package management systems, as it avoided installation failure due to missing dependencies, a type of dependency hell.
[src:deb-packaging/apt-software] Another distinction is the retrieval of packages from remote repositories.
[src:deb-packaging/apt-software] APT uses a location configuration file (`/etc/apt/sources.list`) to locate the desired packages, which might be available on the network or a removable storage medium, for example, and retrieve them, and also obtain information about available (but not installed) packages.
[src:deb-packaging/apt-software] APT provides other command options to override decisions made by apt-get's conflict resolution system.
[src:deb-packaging/apt-software] One option is to force a particular version of a package.
[src:deb-packaging/apt-software] This can downgrade a package and render dependent software inoperable, so the user must be careful.
[src:deb-packaging/apt-software] Finally, the `apt_preferences` mechanism allows the user to create an alternative installation policy for individual packages.
[src:deb-packaging/apt-software] The user can specify packages using a POSIX regular expression.
[src:deb-packaging/apt-software] APT searches its cached list of packages and lists the dependencies that must be installed or updated.
[src:deb-packaging/apt-software] APT retrieves, configures and installs the dependencies automatically.
[src:deb-packaging/apt-software] Triggers are the treatment of deferred actions.
[src:deb-packaging/apt-software] `/etc/apt` contains the APT configuration folders and files.
[src:deb-packaging/apt-software] `apt-config` is the APT Configuration Query program.
[src:deb-packaging/apt-software] `apt-config dump` shows the configuration.
[src:deb-packaging/deb-file-format] Debian packages are standard Unix ar archives that include two tar archives.
[src:deb-packaging/deb-file-format] One archive holds the control information and another contains the installable data.
[src:deb-packaging/deb-file-format] dpkg provides the basic functionality for installing and manipulating Debian packages.
[src:deb-packaging/deb-file-format] Generally end users don't manage packages directly with dpkg but instead use the APT package management software or other APT front-ends such as aptitude (nCurses) and synaptic (GTK).
[src:deb-packaging/deb-file-format] Debian packages can be converted into other package formats and vice versa using alien, and created from source code using checkinstall or the Debian Package Maker.
[src:deb-packaging/deb-file-format] Some core Debian packages are available as **udeb**s ("micro debs"), and are typically used only for bootstrapping a Debian installation.
[src:deb-packaging/deb-file-format] Although these files use the *udeb* filename extension, they adhere to the same structure specification as ordinary *deb* files.
[src:deb-packaging/deb-file-format] However, unlike their *deb* counterparts, *udeb* packages contain only essential functional files.
[src:deb-packaging/deb-file-format] In particular, documentation files are normally omitted.
[src:deb-packaging/deb-file-format] *udeb* packages are not installable on a standard Debian system, but are used in Debian-Installer.
[src:deb-packaging/deb-file-format] Prior to Debian 0.93, a package consisted of a file header and two concatenated gzip archives.
[src:deb-packaging/deb-file-format] Since Debian 0.93, a deb package is implemented as an ar archive.
[src:deb-packaging/deb-file-format] **control archive** - A tar archive named `control.tar` contains the maintainer scripts and the package meta-information (package name, version, dependencies and maintainer).
[src:deb-packaging/deb-file-format] Compressing the archive with gzip or xz and zstd is supported.
[src:deb-packaging/deb-file-format] The file extension changes to indicate the compression method.
[src:deb-packaging/deb-file-format] **data archive** - A tar archive named `data.tar` contains the actual installable files.
[src:deb-packaging/deb-file-format] Compressing the archive with gzip, bzip2, lzma or xz and zstd is supported.
[src:deb-packaging/deb-file-format] Debian-based distributions support OpenPGP signature verification of signed Debian packages, but most (if not all) have this feature disabled by default.
[src:deb-packaging/deb-file-format] Instead packages are verified by signing the repository metadata (i.e.
[src:deb-packaging/deb-file-format] The metadata files in turn include checksums for the repository files as a means to verify authenticity of the files.
[src:deb-packaging/deb-file-format] Currently there are two different implementations for signing individual packages.
[src:deb-packaging/deb-file-format] The first is done via the debsigs / debsig-verify toolset, which is supported by dpkg.
[src:deb-packaging/deb-file-format] The second is done through the dpkg-sig program which is not supported by dpkg, so the packages have to be manually checked with the dpkg-sig program.
[src:deb-packaging/deb-file-format] Both formats add new sections to the ar archive to store the signature information, but the formats are not compatible with one another.
[src:deb-packaging/deb-file-format] Neither of the modifications to the package format are listed in the official Debian handbook or man page about the binary package format.
[src:deb-packaging/digital-signature] A **digital signature** is a mathematical scheme for verifying the authenticity of digital messages or documents.
[src:deb-packaging/digital-signature] A valid digital signature on a message gives a recipient confidence that the message came from a sender known to the recipient.
[src:deb-packaging/digital-signature] Digital signatures are a type of public-key cryptography, and are commonly used for software distribution, financial transactions, contract management software, and in other cases where it is important to detect forgery or tampering.
[src:deb-packaging/digital-signature] Digital signatures are often used to implement electronic signatures, which include any electronic data that carries the intent of a signature, but not all electronic signatures use digital signatures.
[src:deb-packaging/digital-signature] *Security* (existential unforgeability under chosen-message attack, or EUF-CMA): It should be computationally infeasible to generate a valid signature for a party without knowing that party's private key.
[src:deb-packaging/digital-signature] Here 1*n* refers to a unary number in the formalism of computational complexity theory.
[src:deb-packaging/digital-signature] where *A**S*(*sk*, · ) denotes that *A* has access to the oracle, *S*(*sk*, · ), *Q* denotes the set of the queries on *S* made by *A*, which knows the public key, *pk*, and the security parameter, *n*, and *x* ∉ *Q* denotes that the adversary may not directly query the string, *x*, on *S*.
[src:deb-packaging/digital-signature] In 1976, Whitfield Diffie and Martin Hellman first described the notion of a digital signature scheme, although they only conjectured that such schemes existed based on functions that are trapdoor one-way permutations.
[src:deb-packaging/digital-signature] Soon afterwards, Ronald Rivest, Adi Shamir, and Len Adleman invented the RSA algorithm, which could be used to produce primitive digital signatures (although only as a proof-of-concept – "plain" RSA signatures are not secure).
[src:deb-packaging/digital-signature] The first widely marketed software package to offer digital signature was Lotus Notes 1.0, released in 1989, which used the RSA algorithm.
[src:deb-packaging/digital-signature] Other digital signature schemes were soon developed after RSA, the earliest being Lamport signatures, Merkle signatures (also known as "Merkle trees" or simply "Hash trees"), and Rabin signatures.
[src:deb-packaging/digital-signature] In 1988, Shafi Goldwasser, Silvio Micali, and Ronald Rivest became the first to rigorously define the security requirements of digital signature schemes.
[src:deb-packaging/digital-signature] They described a hierarchy of attack models for signature schemes, and also presented the GMR signature scheme, the first that could be proved to prevent even an existential forgery against a chosen message attack, which is the currently accepted security definition for signature schemes.
[src:deb-packaging/digital-signature] The first such scheme which is not built on trapdoor functions but rather on a family of function with a much weaker required property of one-way permutation was presented by Moni Naor and Moti Yung.
[src:deb-packaging/digital-signature] One digital signature scheme (of many) is based on RSA.
[src:deb-packaging/digital-signature] To create signature keys, generate an RSA key pair containing a modulus, *N*, that is the product of two random secret distinct large primes, along with integers, *e* and *d*, such that *e* *d* ≡ 1 (mod *φ*(*N*)), where *φ* is Euler's totient function.
[src:deb-packaging/digital-signature] The signer's public key consists of *N* and *e*, and the signer's secret key contains *d*.
[src:deb-packaging/digital-signature] Used directly, this type of signature scheme is vulnerable to key-only existential forgery attack.
[src:deb-packaging/digital-signature] To create a forgery, the attacker picks a random signature σ and uses the verification procedure to determine the message, *m*, corresponding to that signature.
[src:deb-packaging/digital-signature] In practice, however, this type of signature is not used directly, but rather, the message to be signed is first hashed to produce a short digest, that is then padded to larger width comparable to *N*, then signed with the reverse trapdoor function.
[src:deb-packaging/digital-signature] This forgery attack, then, only produces the padded hash function output that corresponds to σ, but not a message that leads to that value, which does not lead to an attack.
[src:deb-packaging/digital-signature] In the random oracle model, hash-then-sign (an idealized version of that practice where hash and padding combined have close to *N* possible outputs), this form of signature is existentially unforgeable, even against a chosen-plaintext attack.
[src:deb-packaging/digital-signature] There are several reasons to sign such a hash (or message digest) instead of the whole document.
[src:deb-packaging/digital-signature] The signature will be much shorter and thus save time since hashing is generally much faster than signing in practice.
[src:deb-packaging/digital-signature] A hash function can be used to convert an arbitrary input into the proper format.
[src:deb-packaging/digital-signature] Without the hash function, the text "to be signed" may have to be split (separated) in blocks small enough for the signature scheme to act on them directly.
[src:deb-packaging/digital-signature] However, the receiver of the signed blocks is not able to recognize if all the blocks are present and in the appropriate order.
[src:deb-packaging/digital-signature] As organizations move away from paper documents with ink signatures or authenticity stamps, digital signatures can provide added assurances of the evidence to provenance, identity, and status of an electronic document as well as acknowledging informed consent and approval by a signatory.
[src:deb-packaging/digital-signature] The United States Government Printing Office (GPO) publishes electronic versions of the budget, public and private laws, and congressional bills with digital signatures.
[src:deb-packaging/digital-signature] Universities including Penn State, University of Chicago, and Stanford are publishing electronic student transcripts with digital signatures.
[src:deb-packaging/digital-signature] A message may have letterhead or a handwritten signature identifying its sender, but letterheads and handwritten signatures can be copied and pasted onto forged messages.
[src:deb-packaging/digital-signature] Even legitimate messages may be modified in transit.
[src:deb-packaging/digital-signature] With a digital signature scheme, the central office can arrange beforehand to have a public key on file whose private key is known only to the branch office.
[src:deb-packaging/digital-signature] The branch office can later sign a message and the central office can use the public key to verify the signed message was not a forgery before acting on it.
[src:deb-packaging/digital-signature] A forger who *doesn't* know the sender's private key can't sign a different message, or even change a single digit in an existing message without making the recipient's signature verification fail.
[src:deb-packaging/digital-signature] Non-repudiation, or more specifically non-repudiation of origin, is an important aspect of digital signatures.
[src:deb-packaging/digital-signature] By this property, an entity that has signed some information cannot at a later time deny having signed it.
[src:deb-packaging/digital-signature] Similarly, access to the public key only does not enable a fraudulent party to fake a valid signature.
[src:deb-packaging/digital-signature] Note that these authentication, non-repudiation etc. properties rely on the secret key *not having been revoked* prior to its usage.
[src:deb-packaging/digital-signature] Public revocation of a key-pair is a required ability, else leaked secret keys would continue to implicate the claimed owner of the key-pair.
[src:deb-packaging/digital-signature] Checking revocation status requires an "online" check; e.g., checking a certificate revocation list or via the Online Certificate Status Protocol.
[src:deb-packaging/digital-signature] Very roughly this is analogous to a vendor who receives credit-cards first checking online with the credit-card issuer to find if a given card has been reported lost or stolen.
[src:deb-packaging/digital-signature] Of course, with stolen key pairs, the theft is often discovered only after the secret key's use, e.g., to sign a bogus certificate for espionage purpose.
[src:deb-packaging/digital-signature] In a *known message* attack, the attacker is given valid signatures for a variety of messages known by the attacker but not chosen by the attacker.
[src:deb-packaging/digital-signature] In an *adaptive chosen message* attack, the attacker first learns signatures on arbitrary messages of the attacker's choice.
[src:deb-packaging/digital-signature] A universal forgery attack results in the ability to forge signatures for any message.
[src:deb-packaging/digital-signature] A selective forgery attack results in a signature on a message of the adversary's choice.
[src:deb-packaging/digital-signature] An existential forgery merely results in some valid message/signature pair not already known to the adversary.
[src:deb-packaging/digital-signature] The strongest notion of security, therefore, is security against existential forgery under an adaptive chosen message attack.
[src:deb-packaging/digital-signature] All public key / private key cryptosystems depend entirely on keeping the private key secret.
[src:deb-packaging/digital-signature] A more secure alternative is to store the private key on a smart card.
[src:deb-packaging/digital-signature] Many smart cards are designed to be tamper-resistant (although some designs have been broken, notably by Ross Anderson and his students).
[src:deb-packaging/digital-signature] In a typical digital signature implementation, the hash calculated from the document is sent to the smart card, whose CPU signs the hash using the stored private key of the user, and then returns the signed hash.
[src:deb-packaging/digital-signature] Typically, a user must activate their smart card by entering a personal identification number or PIN code (thus providing two-factor authentication).
[src:deb-packaging/digital-signature] It can be arranged that the private key never leaves the smart card, although this is not always implemented.
[src:deb-packaging/digital-signature] If the smart card is stolen, the thief will still need the PIN code to generate a digital signature.
[src:deb-packaging/digital-signature] This reduces the security of the scheme to that of the PIN system, although it still requires an attacker to possess the card.
[src:deb-packaging/digital-signature] A mitigating factor is that private keys, if generated and stored on smart cards, are usually regarded as difficult to copy, and are assumed to exist in exactly one copy.
[src:deb-packaging/digital-signature] Thus, the loss of the smart card may be detected by the owner and the corresponding certificate can be immediately revoked.
[src:deb-packaging/digital-signature] Private keys that are protected by software only may be easier to copy, and such compromises are far more difficult to detect.
[src:deb-packaging/digital-signature] Entering a PIN code to activate the smart card commonly requires a numeric keypad.
[src:deb-packaging/digital-signature] Some card readers have their own numeric keypad.
[src:deb-packaging/digital-signature] This is safer than using a card reader integrated into a PC, and then entering the PIN using that computer's keyboard.
[src:deb-packaging/digital-signature] Readers with a numeric keypad are meant to circumvent the eavesdropping threat where the computer might be running a keystroke logger, potentially compromising the PIN code.
[src:deb-packaging/digital-signature] Specialized card readers are also less vulnerable to tampering with their software or hardware and are often EAL3 certified.
[src:deb-packaging/digital-signature] Smart card design is an active field, and there are smart card schemes which are intended to avoid these particular problems, despite having few security proofs so far.
[src:deb-packaging/digital-signature] One of the main differences between a digital signature and a written signature is that the user does not "see" what they sign.
[src:deb-packaging/digital-signature] The user application presents a hash code to be signed by the digital signing algorithm using the private key.
[src:deb-packaging/digital-signature] An attacker who gains control of the user's PC can possibly replace the user application with a foreign substitute, in effect replacing the user's own communications with those of the attacker.
[src:deb-packaging/digital-signature] This could allow a malicious application to trick a user into signing any document by displaying the user's original on-screen, but presenting the attacker's own documents to the signing application.
[src:deb-packaging/digital-signature] To protect against this scenario, an authentication system can be set up between the user's application (word processor, email client, etc.) and the signing application.
[src:deb-packaging/digital-signature] The general idea is to provide some means for both the user application and signing application to verify each other's integrity.
[src:deb-packaging/digital-signature] For example, the signing application may require all requests to come from digitally signed binaries.
[src:deb-packaging/digital-signature] One of the main differences between a cloud based digital signature service and a locally provided one is risk.
[src:deb-packaging/digital-signature] Many risk averse companies, including governments, financial and medical institutions, and payment processors require more secure standards, like FIPS 140-2 level 3 and FIPS 201 certification, to ensure the signature is validated and secure.
[src:deb-packaging/digital-signature] Technically speaking, a digital signature applies to a string of bits, whereas humans and applications "believe" that they sign the semantic interpretation of those bits.
[src:deb-packaging/digital-signature] In order to be semantically interpreted, the bit string must be transformed into a form that is meaningful for humans and applications, and this is done through a combination of hardware and software based processes on a computer system.
[src:deb-packaging/digital-signature] The problem is that the semantic interpretation of bits can change as a function of the processes used to transform the bits into semantic content.
[src:deb-packaging/digital-signature] It is relatively easy to change the interpretation of a digital document by implementing changes on the computer system where the document is being processed.
[src:deb-packaging/digital-signature] From a semantic perspective this creates uncertainty about what exactly has been signed.
[src:deb-packaging/digital-signature] WYSIWYS (What You See Is What You Sign) means that the semantic interpretation of a signed message cannot be changed.
[src:deb-packaging/digital-signature] In particular this also means that a message cannot contain hidden information that the signer is unaware of, and that can be revealed after the signature has been applied.
[src:deb-packaging/digital-signature] WYSIWYS is a requirement for the validity of digital signatures, but this requirement is difficult to guarantee because of the increasing complexity of modern computer systems.
[src:deb-packaging/digital-signature] The term WYSIWYS was coined by Peter Landrock and Torben Pedersen to describe some of the principles in delivering secure and legally binding digital signatures for Pan-European projects.
[src:deb-packaging/digital-signature] Digital signatures cryptographically bind an electronic identity to an electronic document and the digital signature cannot be copied to another document.
[src:deb-packaging/digital-signature] Paper contracts sometimes have the ink signature block on the last page, and the previous pages may be replaced after a signature is applied.
[src:deb-packaging/digital-signature] Digital signatures can be applied to an entire document, such that the digital signature on the last page will indicate tampering if any data on any of the pages have been altered, but this can also be achieved by signing with ink and numbering all pages of the contract.
[src:deb-packaging/digital-signature] Quality implementations: An implementation of a good algorithm (or protocol) with mistake(s) will not work.
[src:deb-packaging/digital-signature] Users (and their software) must carry out the signature protocol properly.
[src:deb-packaging/digital-signature] The private key must remain private: If the private key becomes known to any other party, that party can produce *perfect* digital signatures of anything.
[src:deb-packaging/digital-signature] The public key owner must be verifiable: A public key associated with Bob actually came from Bob.
[src:deb-packaging/digital-signature] This is commonly done using a public key infrastructure (PKI) and the public key↔user association is attested by the operator of the PKI (called a certificate authority).
[src:deb-packaging/digital-signature] For 'open' PKIs in which anyone can request such an attestation (universally embodied in a cryptographically protected public key certificate), the possibility of mistaken attestation is non-trivial.
[src:deb-packaging/digital-signature] Commercial PKI operators have suffered several publicly known problems.
[src:deb-packaging/digital-signature] Such mistakes could lead to falsely signed, and thus wrongly attributed, documents.
[src:deb-packaging/digital-signature] 'Closed' PKI systems are more expensive, but less easily subverted in this way.
[src:deb-packaging/digital-signature] Only if all of these conditions are met will a digital signature actually be any evidence of who sent the message, and therefore of their assent to its contents.
[src:deb-packaging/digital-signature] Legal enactment cannot change this reality of the existing engineering possibilities, though some such have not reflected this actuality.
[src:deb-packaging/digital-signature] The first appears to have been in Utah in the United States, followed closely by the states Massachusetts and California.
[src:deb-packaging/digital-signature] Other countries have also passed statutes or issued regulations in this area as well and the UN has had an active model law project for some time.
[src:deb-packaging/digital-signature] Adoption of technical standards for digital signatures have lagged behind much of the legislation, delaying a more or less unified engineering position on interoperability, algorithm choice, key lengths, and so on what the engineering is attempting to provide.
[src:deb-packaging/digital-signature] Some industries have established common interoperability standards for the use of digital signatures between members of the industry and with regulators.
[src:deb-packaging/digital-signature] These include the Automotive Network Exchange for the automobile industry and the SAFE-BioPharma Association for the healthcare industry.
[src:deb-packaging/digital-signature] In several countries, a digital signature has a status somewhat like that of a traditional pen and paper signature, as in the 1999 EU digital signature directive and 2014 EU follow-on legislation.
[src:deb-packaging/digital-signature] Generally, these provisions mean that anything digitally signed legally binds the signer of the document to the terms therein.
[src:deb-packaging/digital-signature] For that reason, it is often thought best to use separate key pairs for encrypting and signing.
[src:deb-packaging/digital-signature] Using the encryption key pair, a person can engage in an encrypted conversation (e.g., regarding a real estate transaction), but the encryption does not legally sign every message he or she sends.
[src:deb-packaging/digital-signature] Only when both parties come to an agreement do they sign a contract with their signing keys, and only then are they legally bound by the terms of a specific document.
[src:deb-packaging/digital-signature] After signing, the document can be sent over the encrypted link.
[src:deb-packaging/digital-signature] If a signing key is lost or compromised, it can be revoked to mitigate any future transactions.
[src:deb-packaging/digital-signature] If an encryption key is lost, a backup or key escrow should be utilized to continue viewing encrypted content.
[src:deb-packaging/digital-signature] Signing keys should never be backed up or escrowed unless the backup destination is securely encrypted.
[src:deb-packaging/dpkg] `dpkg` (Debian Package) itself is a low-level tool.
[src:deb-packaging/dpkg] Advanced Package Tool (APT), a higher-level tool, is more commonly used than `dpkg` as it can fetch packages from remote locations and deal with complex package relations, such as dependency resolution.
[src:deb-packaging/dpkg] Frontends for APT, like aptitude (ncurses) and synaptic (GTK), are used for their user-friendly interfaces.
[src:deb-packaging/dpkg] The Debian package *dpkg* provides the `dpkg` program, and several other programs needed for runtime functioning of the packaging system, including `dpkg-deb`, `dpkg-split`, `dpkg-query`, `dpkg-statoverride`, `dpkg-divert` and `dpkg-trigger`.
[src:deb-packaging/dpkg] It also includes the programs such as `update-alternatives` and `start-stop-daemon`.
[src:deb-packaging/dpkg] The Debian package "dpkg-dev" includes the many build tools described below.
[src:deb-packaging/dpkg] The first attempt at a package management system for Linux was possibly the development of StopAlop by Greg Wettstein at the Roger Maris Cancer Center in Fargo, North Dakota.
[src:deb-packaging/dpkg] It provided inspiration to create dpkg. dpkg was originally created by Ian Murdock in January 1994 as a Shell script.
[src:deb-packaging/dpkg] Matt Welsh, Carl Streeter and Ian Murdock then rewrote it in Perl, and then later the main part was rewritten in C by Ian Jackson in 1994.
[src:deb-packaging/dpkg] The name *dpkg* was originally a shortening of *Debian package*, but the meaning of that phrase has evolved significantly, as dpkg the software is orthogonal to the deb package format and the Debian Policy Manual which defines how Debian packages behave in Debian.
[src:deb-packaging/dpkg] dpkg-dev contains a series of development tools needed to unpack, build, and upload Debian source code packages.
[src:deb-packaging/dpkg] The dpkg source package also contains *dselect*, a frontend software.
[src:deb-packaging/dpkg] The `install-info` program used to be included in the dpkg software package, but was later removed as it became developed and distributed separately, as part of GNU Texinfo.
[src:deb-packaging/software-repository] A **software repository**, or **repo** for short, is a storage location for software packages.
[src:deb-packaging/software-repository] Often a table of contents is also stored, along with metadata.
[src:deb-packaging/software-repository] A software repository is typically managed by source or version control, or repository managers.
[src:deb-packaging/software-repository] Package managers allow automatically installing and updating repositories, sometimes called "packages".
[src:deb-packaging/software-repository] Many software publishers and other organizations maintain servers on the Internet for this purpose, either free of charge or for a subscription fee.
[src:deb-packaging/software-repository] Repositories may be solely for particular programs, such as CPAN for the Perl programming language, or for an entire operating system.
[src:deb-packaging/software-repository] Operators of such repositories typically provide a package management system, tools intended to search for, install and otherwise manipulate software packages from the repositories.
[src:deb-packaging/software-repository] For example, many Linux distributions use Advanced Packaging Tool (APT), commonly found in Debian based distributions, or Yellowdog Updater, Modified (yum) found in Red Hat based distributions.
[src:deb-packaging/software-repository] There are also multiple independent package management systems, such as pacman, used in Arch Linux and equo, found in Sabayon Linux.
[src:deb-packaging/software-repository] As software repositories are designed to include useful packages, major repositories are designed to be malware free.
[src:deb-packaging/software-repository] If a computer is configured to use a digitally signed repository from a reputable vendor, and is coupled with an appropriate permissions system, this significantly reduces the threat of malware to these systems.
[src:deb-packaging/software-repository] As a side effect, many systems that have these abilities do not need anti-malware software such as antivirus software.
[src:deb-packaging/software-repository] Most major Linux distributions have many repositories around the world that mirror the main repository.
[src:deb-packaging/software-repository] At client side, a package manager helps installing from and updating the repositories.
[src:deb-packaging/software-repository] A package management system is different from a package development process.
[src:deb-packaging/software-repository] A typical use of a package management system is to facilitate the integration of code from possibly different sources into a coherent stand-alone operating unit.
[src:deb-packaging/software-repository] Thus, a package management system might be used to produce a distribution of Linux, possibly a distribution tailored to a specific restricted application.
[src:deb-packaging/software-repository] A package development process, by contrast, is used to manage the co-development of code and documentation of a collection of functions or routines with a common theme, producing thereby a package of software functions that typically will not be complete and usable by themselves.
[src:deb-packaging/software-repository] A good package development process will help users conform to good documentation and coding practices, integrating some level of unit testing.
[src:deb-packaging/software-repository] The following table lists a few languages with repositories for contributed software.
[src:deb-packaging/software-repository] The "Autochecks" column describes the routine checks done.
[src:deb-packaging/software-repository] Very few people have the ability to test their software under multiple operating systems with different versions of the core code and with other contributed packages they may use.
[src:deb-packaging/software-repository] For the R programming language, the Comprehensive R Archive Network (CRAN) runs tests routinely.
[src:deb-packaging/software-repository] To understand how this is valuable, imagine a situation with two developers, Sally and John.
[src:deb-packaging/software-repository] Sally only runs the current version of the software under one version of Microsoft Windows, and has only tested it in that environment.
[src:deb-packaging/software-repository] At more or less regular intervals, CRAN tests Sally's contribution under a dozen combinations of operating systems and versions of the core R language software.
[src:deb-packaging/software-repository] If one of them generates an error, she gets that error message.
[src:deb-packaging/software-repository] With luck, that error message details may provide enough input to allow enable a fix for the error, even if she cannot replicate it with her current hardware and software.
[src:deb-packaging/software-repository] Next, suppose John contributes to the repository a package B that uses a package A.
[src:deb-packaging/software-repository] Package B passes all the tests and is made available to users.
[src:deb-packaging/software-repository] Later, Sally submits an improved version of A, which breaks B.
[src:deb-packaging/software-repository] The autochecks make it possible to provide information to John so he can fix the problem.
[src:deb-packaging/software-repository] This example exposes both a strength and a weakness in the R contributed-package system: CRAN supports this kind of automated testing of contributed packages, but packages contributed to CRAN need not specify the versions of other contributed packages that they use.
[src:deb-packaging/software-repository] Procedures for requesting specific versions of packages exist, but contributors might not use those procedures.
[src:deb-packaging/software-repository] Beyond this, a repository such as CRAN running regular checks of contributed packages actually provides an extensive if *ad hoc* test suite for development versions of the core language.
[src:deb-packaging/software-repository] If Sally (in the example above) gets an error message she does not understand or thinks is inappropriate, especially from a development version of the language, she can (and often does with R) ask the core development-team for the language for help.
[src:deb-packaging/software-repository] In this way, the repository can contribute to improving the quality of the core language software.
[src:deb-packaging/software-repository] Package managers help manage repositories and the distribution of them.
[src:deb-packaging/software-repository] If a repository is updated, a package manager will usually allow a user to update that repository through the manager.
[src:deb-packaging/software-repository] It also helps to manage things such as dependencies between other repositories.
[src:deb-packaging/software-repository] In an enterprise environment, a software repository is usually used to store artifacts, or to mirror external repositories which may be inaccessible due to security restrictions.
[src:deb-packaging/software-repository] One example is Sonatype Nexus Repository.
[src:deb-packaging/software-repository] At server side, a software repository is typically managed by source control or repository managers.
[src:deb-packaging/software-repository] Some of the repository managers allow to aggregate other repository location into one URL and provide a caching proxy.
[src:deb-packaging/software-repository] When doing continuous builds many artifacts are produced and often centrally stored, so automatically deleting the ones which are not released is important.
[src:deb-packaging/software-repository] As part of the development lifecycle, source code is continuously being built into binary artifacts using continuous integration.
[src:deb-packaging/software-repository] This may interact with a binary repository manager much like a developer would by getting artifacts from the repositories and pushing builds there.
[src:deb-packaging/software-repository] Artifacts and packages inherently mean different things.
[src:deb-packaging/software-repository] Artifacts are simply an output or collection of files (ex.
[src:deb-packaging/software-repository] JAR, WAR, DLLS, RPM etc.) and one of those files may contain metadata (e.g.
[src:deb-packaging/software-repository] Whereas packages are a single archive file in a well-defined format (ex.
[src:deb-packaging/software-repository] NuGet) that contain files appropriate for the package type (ex.
[src:deb-packaging/software-repository] Many artifacts result from builds but other types are crucial as well.
[src:deb-packaging/software-repository] Packages are essentially one of two things: a library or an application.
[src:deb-packaging/software-repository] Compared to source files, binary artifacts are often larger by orders of magnitude, they are rarely deleted or overwritten (except for rare cases such as snapshots or nightly builds), and they are usually accompanied by much metadata such as id, package name, version, license and more.
[src:deb-packaging/software-repository] Metadata describes a binary artifact, is stored and specified separately from the artifact itself, and can have several additional uses.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] Most free and open-source software packages, including MediaWiki, treat versions as a series of individual numbers, separated by periods, with a progression such as 1.8.1, 1.9.0.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] On the other hand, some software packages identify releases by decimal numbers: 1.8, 1.81, 1.82.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] Developers may choose to jump multiple minor versions at a time to indicate that significant features have been added or for marketing purposes.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] Version numbers are often used to identify copies of a software product and compare them against another copy in a collaborative version control system.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] Within software development teams, version control is used to keep track of incrementally-different versions of information in order to be able to roll any changes back.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] Modern computer software is often tracked using two different software versioning schemes: an internal version number, which may be incremented many times in a single day, and a release version, which typically changes far less often.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] Historically, file numbers were especially used in public administration and corporations to uniquely identify files or cases.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] This practice was introduced to computer files for the first time with MIT's ITS file system, later the TENEX file system for the PDP-10 in 1972.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] In the 21st century, more programmers started to use a standardized version policy, such as the semantic versioning policy, which is particularly useful when using software libraries, frameworks, and command-line applications.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] File numbers were used especially in public administration, as well as companies, to uniquely identify files or cases.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] For computer files this practice was introduced for the first time with MIT's ITS file system, later the TENEX filesystem for the PDP-10 in 1972.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] Later lists of files including their versions were added, and dependencies amongst them.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] Linux distributions like Debian, with its dpkg, early on created package management software which could resolve dependencies between their packages.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] Debian's first try was that a package knew other packages which depended on it.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] From 1994 on this idea was inverted, so a package that knew the packages it needed.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] When installing a package, dependency resolution was used to automatically calculate the packages needed as well, and install them with the desired package.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] To facilitate upgrades, minimum package versions were introduced.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] Thus the numbering scheme needed to tell which version was newer than the required one.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] In sequence-based software versioning schemes, each software release is assigned a unique identifier that consists of one or more sequences of numbers or letters.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] This is the extent of the commonality; schemes vary widely in areas such as the number of sequences, the attribution of meaning to individual sequences, and the means of incrementing the sequences.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] In some schemes, sequence-based identifiers are used to convey the significance of changes between releases.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] Semantic versioning (aka SemVer) is a widely adopted version scheme that encodes a version by a three-part version number (Major.Minor.Patch), an optional prerelease tag, and an optional build meta tag.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] In this scheme, risk and functionality are the measures of significance.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] Breaking changes are indicated by increasing the major number (high risk); new, non-breaking features increment the minor number (medium risk); and all other non-breaking changes increment the patch number (lowest risk).
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] The presence of a prerelease tag (-alpha, -beta) indicates substantial risk, as does a major number of zero (0.y.z), which is used to indicate a work-in-progress that may contain any level of potentially breaking changes (highest risk).
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] As an example of inferring compatibility from a SemVer version, software which relies on version 2.1.5 of an API is compatible with version 2.2.3, but not necessarily with 3.2.4.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] A fourth number may also be used to denote the software build, as was the case for Adobe Flash.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] Some companies also include the build date and letters and other characters, such as Lotus 1-2-3 Release 1a.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] Developers may choose to jump multiple minor versions at a time to indicate that significant features have been added, but are not enough to warrant incrementing a major version number; for example, Internet Explorer 5 from 5.1 to 5.5 or Adobe Photoshop 5 to 5.5.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] A different approach is to use the *major* and *minor* numbers along with an alphanumeric string denoting the release type, e.g.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] A software release train using this approach might look like 0.5, 0.6, 0.7, 0.8, 0.9 → 1.0b1, 1.0b2 (with some fixes), 1.0b3 (with more fixes) → 1.0rc1 (if it is stable *enough*), 1.0rc2 (if more bugs are found) → 1.0.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] It is a common practice in this scheme to lock out new features and breaking changes during the release candidate phases and, for some teams, even betas are locked down to bug fixes only, to ensure convergence on the target release.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] Again, in these examples, the definition of what constitutes a "major" as opposed to a "minor" change is entirely subjective and up to the author, as is what defines a "build", or how a "revision" differs from a "minor" change.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] : The most recent interface number that the library implements.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] : The implementation number of the current interface.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] : The difference between the newest and oldest interfaces that the library implements.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] : others may use a different meaning or simply ignore it.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] A similar problem of relative change significance and versioning nomenclature exists in book publishing, where edition numbers or names can be chosen based on varying criteria.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] In most proprietary software, the first released version of a software product has version 1.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] Some projects use the major version number to indicate incompatible releases.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] Two examples are Apache Portable Runtime (APR) and the FarCry CMS.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] Often programmers write new software to be backward compatible.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] For example, IBM z/OS is designed to work properly with 3 consecutive major versions of the operating system running in the same sysplex.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] This enables people who run a high availability computer cluster to keep most of the computers up and running while one machine at a time is shut down, upgraded, and restored to service.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] Often packet headers and file format include a version number – sometimes the same as the version number of the software that wrote it; other times a "protocol version number" independent of the software version number.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] The code to handle old deprecated protocols and file formats is often seen as cruft.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] Software in the experimental stage (alpha or beta) often uses a zero in the first ("major") position of the sequence to designate its status.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] However, this scheme is only useful for the early stages, not for upcoming releases with established software where the version number has already progressed past 0.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] The two purely numeric forms remove the special logic required to handle the comparison of "alpha < beta < rc < no prefix" as found in semantic versioning, at the cost of clarity.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] Most free and open-source software packages, including MediaWiki, treat versions as a series of individual numbers, separated by periods, with a progression such as 1.7.0, 1.8.0, 1.8.1, 1.9.0, 1.10.0, 1.11.0, 1.11.1, 1.11.2, and so on.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] On the other hand, some software packages identify releases by decimal numbers: 1.7, 1.8, 1.81, 1.82, 1.9, etc.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] Decimal versions were common in the 1980s, for example with NetWare, DOS, and Microsoft Windows, but even in the 2000s have been for example used by Opera and Movable Type.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] In the decimal scheme, 1.81 is the minor version following 1.8, while maintenance releases (i.e. bug fixes only) may be denoted with an alphabetic suffix, such as 1.81a or 1.81b.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] The standard GNU version numbering scheme is major.minor.revision, but Emacs is a notable example using another scheme where the major number (1) was dropped and a *user site* revision was added which is always zero in original Emacs packages but increased by distributors.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] Similarly, Debian package numbers are prefixed with an optional "epoch", which is used to allow the versioning scheme to be changed.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] In some cases, developers may decide to reset the major version number.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] This is sometimes used to denote a new development phase being released.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] For example, *Minecraft* Alpha ran from version 1.0.0 to 1.2.6, and when Beta was released, it reset the major version number and ran from 1.0 to 1.8.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] Once the game was fully released, the major version number again reset to 1.0.0.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] Some projects use negative version numbers.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] One example is the SmartEiffel compiler which started from −1.0 and counted upwards to 0.0.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] To ease sorting, some software packages represent each component of the *major.minor.release* scheme with a fixed width.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] Perl represents its version numbers as a floating-point number; for example, Perl's 5.8.7 release can also be represented as 5.008007.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] This allows a theoretical version of 5.8.10 to be represented as 5.008010.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] Other software packages pack each segment into a fixed bit width; for example, on Microsoft Windows, version number 6.3.9600.16384 would be represented as hexadecimal 0x0006000325804000.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] The floating-point scheme breaks down if any segment of the version number exceeds 999; a packed-binary scheme employing 16 bits apiece breaks down after 65535.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] Between the 1.0 and the 2.6.x series, the Linux kernel used odd minor version numbers to denote development releases and even minor version numbers to denote stable releases.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] For example, Linux 2.3 was a development family of the second major design of the Linux kernel, and Linux 2.4 was the stable release family that Linux 2.3 matured into.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] After the minor version number in the Linux kernel is the release number, in ascending order; for example, Linux 2.4.0 → Linux 2.4.22.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] Since the 2004 release of the 2.6 kernel, Linux no longer uses this system, and has a much shorter release cycle.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] The same odd-even system is used by some other software with long release cycles, such as Node.js up to version 0.12 as well as WineHQ.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] Many projects use a date-based versioning scheme called **Calendar Versioning** (aka **CalVer**).
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] Ubuntu is one example of a project using calendar versioning; Ubuntu 18.04, for example, was released in April 2018.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] This has the advantage of being easily relatable to development schedules and support timelines.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] Some video games also use date as versioning, for example the arcade game *Street Fighter EX*.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] At startup it displays the version number as a date plus a region code, for example *961219 ASIA*.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] When using dates in versioning, for instance, file names, it is common to use the ISO 8601 scheme *YYYY-MM-DD*, as this is easily string-sorted in increasing or decreasing order.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] The Wine project formerly used a date versioning scheme, which used the year followed by the month followed by the day of the release; for example, "Wine 20040505".
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] The earliest development builds of *Minecraft* had a similar version formatting, but instead used DDHHMM, for example rd-131655 was created on the 13th (of May 2009) at 16:21.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] Microsoft Office build numbers are an encoded date: the first two digits indicate the number of months that have passed from the January of the year in which the project started (with each major Office release being a different project), while the last two digits indicate the day of that month.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] So 3419 is the 19th day of the 34th month after the month of January of the year the project started.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] Other examples that identify versions by year include Adobe Illustrator 88 and WordPerfect Office 2003.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] When a year is used to denote version, it is generally for marketing purposes, and an actual version number also exists.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] For example, Windows 95 is internally versioned as MS-DOS 7.00 and Windows 4.00; likewise, Windows 2000 is internally versioned as NT 5.0.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] Some software producers use different schemes to denote releases of their software.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] The Debian project uses a major/minor versioning scheme for releases of its operating system but uses code names from the movie *Toy Story* during development to refer to stable, unstable, and testing releases.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] BLAG Linux and GNU features very large version numbers: major releases have numbers such as 50000 and 60000, while minor releases increase the number by 1 (e.g.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] Alpha and beta releases are given decimal version numbers slightly less than the major release number, such as 19999.00071 for alpha 1 of version 20000, and 29999.50000 for beta 2 of version 30000.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] Urbit uses *Kelvin versioning* (named after the absolute Kelvin temperature scale): software versions start at a high number and count down to version 0, at which point the software is considered finished and no further modifications are made.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] In conjunction with the various versioning schemes listed above, a system for denoting prerelease versions is generally used, as the program makes its way through the stages of the software release life cycle.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] Programs that are in an early stage are often called "alpha" software, after the first letter in the Greek alphabet.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] After they mature but are not yet ready for release, they may be called "beta" software, after the second letter in the Greek alphabet.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] Generally alpha software is tested by developers only, while beta software is distributed for community testing.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] Some systems use numerical versions less than 1 (such as 0.9), to suggest their approach toward a final "1.0" release.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] This is a common convention in open source software.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] However, if the prerelease version is for an existing software package (e.g. version 2.5), then an "a" or "alpha" may be appended to the version number.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] So the alpha version of the 2.5 release might be identified as 2.5a or 2.5.a.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] Version numbers are used in practical terms by the consumer, or client, to identify or compare their copy of the software product against another copy, such as the newest version released by the developer.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] For the programmer or company, versioning is often used on a revision-by-revision basis, where individual parts of the software are compared and contrasted with newer or older revisions of those same parts, often in a collaborative version control system.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] In the 21st century, more programmers started to use a formalized version policy, such as the semantic versioning policy.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] The purpose of such policies is to make it easier for other programmers to know when code changes are likely to break things they have written.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] Such policies are especially important for software libraries and frameworks, but may also be very useful for command-line applications (which may be called from other applications) and for other applications (which may be scripted and/or extended by third parties).
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] A **software release train** is a form of software release schedule in which a number of distinct series of versioned software releases for multiple products are released as a number of different "trains" on a regular schedule.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] Generally, for each product line, a number of different release trains are running at a given time, with each train moving from initial release to eventual maturity and retirement on a planned schedule.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] Users may experiment with a newer release train before adopting it for production, allowing them to experiment with newer, "raw", releases early, while continuing to follow the previous train's point releases for their production systems prior to moving to the new release train as it becomes mature.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] Cisco's IOS software platform used a release train schedule with many distinct trains for many years.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] More recently, a number of other platforms including Firefox and Fenix for Android, Eclipse, LibreOffice, Ubuntu, Fedora, Python, digiKam and VMware have adopted the release train model.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] Software may have an "internal" version number which differs from the version number shown in the product name (and which typically follows version numbering rules more consistently).
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] Windows 10 was initially intended to be NT 6.4, as the earliest Technical Preview build shared to the public is numbered 6.4.9841.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] However, that did not last as the version of Windows 10 was quickly artificially increased to 10.0 to align with the commercial name, resulting in the first released version of the operating system being numbered 10.0.10240.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] Note, however, that Windows NT is only on its fifth major revision, as its first release was numbered 3.1 (to match the then-current Windows release number) and the Windows 10 launching made a version leap from 6.3 to 10.0.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] A relatively common practice is to make major jumps in version numbers for marketing reasons.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] Sometimes software vendors just bypass the 1.0 release or quickly release a release with a subsequent version number because 1.0 software is considered by many customers too immature to trust with production deployments.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] For example, as in the case of dBase II, a product is launched with a version number that implies that it is more mature than it is.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] Other times version numbers are increased to match those of competitors.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] This can be seen in many examples of product version numbering by Microsoft, America Online, Sun Solaris, Java Virtual Machine, SCO Unix, WordPerfect.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] Microsoft Access jumped from version 2.0 to version 7.0, to match the version number of Microsoft Word.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] Another example of keeping up with competitors is when Slackware Linux jumped from version 4 to version 7 in 1999.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] This approach, panned by many because it breaks the semantic significance of the sections of the version number, has been adopted by an increasing number of vendors including Mozilla (for Firefox) and Google (for Google Chrome).
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] Sun also dropped the first digit for Solaris, where Solaris 2.8 (or 2.9) is referred to as Solaris 8 (or 9) in marketing materials.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] A similar jump took place with the Asterisk open-source PBX construction kit in the early 2010s, whose project leads announced that the current version 1.8.x would soon be followed by version 10.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] The free-software and open source communities tend to release software early and often.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] Initial versions are numbers less than 1, with these 0.x version used to convey that the software is incomplete and not reliable enough for general release or usable in its current state.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] Backward-incompatible changes are common with 0.x versions.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] Version 1.0 is used as a major milestone, indicating that the software has at least all major features plus functions the developers wanted to get into that version, and is considered reliable enough for general release.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] A good example of this is the Linux kernel, which was first released as version 0.01 in 1991, and took until 1994 to reach version 1.0.0.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] The developers of the arcade game emulator MAME do not ever intend to release a version 1.0 of the program because there will always be more arcade games to emulate and thus the project can never be truly completed.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] Accordingly, version 0.99 was followed by version 0.100.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] The Python Software Foundation has published PEP 440 – Version Identification and Dependency Specification, outlining their own flexible scheme, that defines an epoch segment, a release segment, prerelease and post-release segments and a development release segment.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] TeX has an idiosyncratic version numbering system, an unusual feature invented by its developer Donald Knuth.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] Since version 3.1, updates have been indicated by adding an extra digit at the end, so that the version number asymptotically approaches the number π, so 3.14 effectively means 3.2 in semantic versioning.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] (This is a form of unary numbering; the version number is the number of digits.) Since 2021, the version number has been 3.141592653.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] This is a reflection of TeX being very stable, and only minor updates are anticipated.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] TeX developer Donald Knuth has stated that the *"absolutely final change (to be made after [his] death)"* will be to change the version number to π, at which point all remaining bugs will become permanent features.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] In a similar way, the version number of Metafont asymptotically approaches Euler's number, e.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] Metafont was also devised by Donald Knuth as a companion to his TeX typesetting system.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] During the era of the classic Mac OS, minor version numbers rarely went beyond ".1".
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] When they did, they usually jumped straight to ".5", suggesting the release was "more significant".
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] Thus, "8.5" was marketed as its own release, representing "Mac OS 8 and a half", and 8.6 effectively meant "8.5.1".
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] Mac OS X departed from this trend, in large part because "X" (the Roman numeral for 10) was in the name of the product.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] As a result, all versions of OS X began with the number 10.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] The first major release of OS X was given the version number 10.0, but the next major release was not 11.0.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] Instead, it was numbered 10.1, followed by 10.2, 10.3, and so on for each subsequent major release.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] Thus the 11th major version of OS X was labeled "10.10".
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] Even though the "X" was dropped from the name as of macOS 10.12, this numbering scheme continued through macOS 10.15.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] Under the "X"-based versioning scheme, the third number (instead of the second) denoted a minor release, and additional updates below this level, as well as updates to a given major version of OS X coming after the release of a new major version, were titled Supplemental Updates.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] The Roman numeral X was concurrently leveraged for marketing purposes across multiple product lines.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] Both QuickTime and Final Cut Pro jumped from version 7 directly to version 10, QuickTime X and Final Cut Pro X.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] Like Mac OS X itself, the products were not upgrades to previous versions, but brand-new programs.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] As with OS X, major releases for these programs incremented the second digit and minor releases were denoted using a third digit.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] The "X" was dropped from Final Cut's name with the release of macOS 11.0 (see below), and QuickTime's branding became moot when the framework was deprecated in favor of AVFoundation in 2011 (the program for playing QuickTime video was only named QuickTime Player from the start).
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] Apple's next macOS release, provisionally numbered 10.16, was officially announced as macOS 11 at WWDC in June 2020, and released in November 2020.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] The following macOS version, macOS Monterey, was released in October 2021 and bumped its major version number to 12.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] In June 2025, Apple announced an unified versioning scheme, using the year next to the release date, similar to model years in vehicles.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] The versions that were released in the fall of 2025 are iOS 26, macOS 26, iPadOS 26, tvOS 26, watchOS 26 and visionOS 26.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] The Microsoft Windows operating system was first labelled with standard version numbers for Windows 1.01 through Windows 3.2.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] After this Microsoft excluded the version number from the product name.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] For Windows 95 (version 4.0), Windows 98 (4.10) and Windows 2000 (5.0), year of the release was included in the product title.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] After Windows 2000, Microsoft created the Windows Server family which continued the year-based style with a difference: For minor releases, Microsoft suffixed "R2" to the title, e.g., Windows Server 2008 R2 (version 6.1).
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] This style had remained consistent to this date.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] The client versions of Windows however did not adopt a consistent style.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] First, they received names with arbitrary alphanumeric suffixes as with Windows Me (4.90), Windows XP (5.1), and Windows Vista (6.0).
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] Then, once again Microsoft adopted incremental numbers in the title, but this time, they were not versioning numbers; the version numbers of Windows 7, Windows 8 and Windows 8.1 are respectively 6.1, 6.2 and 6.3.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] In Windows 10, the version number leaped to 10.0 and subsequent updates to the OS only incremented build number (which is date-based) and update build revision (UBR) number.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] The successor of Windows 10, Windows 11, was released on October 5, 2021.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] Despite being named "11", the new Windows release did not bump its major version number to 11.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] Instead, it stayed at the same version number of 10.0, used by Windows 10.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] Some computer file systems, such as the OpenVMS Filesystem, also keep versions for files.
[src:deb-packaging/software-versioning] Technical drawing and CAD software files may also use some kind of primitive versioning number to keep track of changes.
